, but its history also includes extensive work by such philosophical luminaries as (at least) Socrates, Plato, Aristotle, the Stoics, Aquinas, and (perhaps) Hume and Nietzsche. And this suggests that we should already be in a good position to assess its appeal."—from the IntroductionIn Virtue Ethics, Old and New, ten philosophers seek to enrich the contemporary understanding and development of virtue ethics through a detailed examination of some key contributions from its past. Their essays demonstrate the continuing relevance of the history of moral philosophy to contemporary debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEthicsvCongresses. 0aVirtuevCongresses. 4aHistory. 4aPhilosophy & Religion. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aAnnas, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrisp, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardiner, Stephen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardiner, Stephen M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarris, George W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiggins, Kathleen Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrwin, T. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRussell, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSolomon, Robert C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwanton, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWelchman, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.